-- Pacifica Mesa, Owner of New Mexico Film Studio, Files for Court Protection
-- Dawn McCarty
-- 2010-07-21T12:13:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/pacifica-mesa-owner-of-new-mexico-film-studio-files-for-court-protection.html

          
          
             Pacifica Mesa Studios LLC, the
parent company of the New Mexico complex where the movies “The
Book of Eli” and “Terminator Salvation” were filmed, filed
for bankruptcy protection.  
 The Agoura Hills, California-based company listed assets of
$57.7 million and debt of $104.5 million in Chapter 11 documents
filed yesterday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Woodland Hills,
California. Pacifica Mesa holds the title to  Albuquerque
Studios , a 28-acre site the company valued at $54 million in
court papers.  
 Amalgamated Bank of New York holds an $80 million senior
loan on the property. Workers Realty Trust, owed $23 million, is
the junior partner in the studio’s loan, court papers show.  
 The bankruptcy case is In re Pacifica Mesa Studios LLC, 10-
18827, U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Central District of California
(San Fernando Valley).  
